For the purpose of facilitating an understanding of the invention, there is illustrated in the accompanying drawings a preferred embodiment thereof, from an inspection of which, when considered in connection with the following description, the invention, its construction and operation, and many of its advantages should be readily understood and appreciated.


FIG. 1 is a functional block diagrammatic view of hardware components of a system in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 2 is an illustration of a page of a report of the type with which the present invention may be used;


FIGS. 3A-3C are diagrammatic illustrations of the three main phases of the use of the system of the present invention;


FIG. 4 is a diagrammatic illustration of a pattern abstracted from the report page of FIG. 2;


FIG. 5 is a diagram of the structural hierarchy of the patterns within the report page of FIG. 2;


FIG. 6 is a diagram illustrating the generation of a structure sequence table for the report page of FIG. 2;


FIGS. 7A-7C are diagrams illustrating the process of pattern abstraction from a report like that of FIG. 2;


FIG. 8 is a flow chart diagram of the automatic generation of a line species inventory in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 9 is a flow chart diagram of the software routine for creating a population of text line species in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 10 is a diagram illustrating the concept of line species coverage in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 11 is a diagram illustrating the concept of line species similarity in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 12 is a flow chart diagram illustrating a software routine for classification of a text line to a single pattern in accordance with the present invention; and


FIG. 13 is a flow chart diagram illustrating software routine for improving a line species inventory in accordance with the invention.

(1) a collection of text lines that are samples of it, which samples are initially automatically selected by the system and may also be added by the user;


(2) a template that provides a statistical distribution of character classes in the pattern; and


(3) a collection of fields which, together, form a meta-definition based on the samples.

(b) ambiguous match--the text line was perfectly included by more than one Line Species, the most similar of which (using DOM) is picked by the system;


(c) fuzzy match--the text line was not perfectly included by any Line Species in the Inventory, but was found to be similar (DOM was greater than a predefined threshold) to a particular Line Species; and


(d) unmatched--the text line was neither included by, nor was it similar to any Line Species in the Inventory.
